sequenceDiagram
    autonumber
    participant UT as User Terminal<br/>(Berlin, Germany)
    participant IS as Ingress Satellite<br/>(overhead Berlin)
    participant ISL as ISL Network<br/>(hop-by-hop)
    participant ES as Egress Satellite<br/>(over nearest GS)
    participant GS as Ground Station<br/>(Frankfurt, DE)
    participant POP as PoP Frankfurt<br/>(nearest to USER)
    participant G as Google<br/>(Mountain View, CA)

    Note over UT: HAS: satellite ephemeris<br/>(from ground control),<br/>antenna pointing data
    Note over IS: HAS: forwarding table<br/>(dest GS -> next hop),<br/>from ground control
    Note over GS: HAS: fixed fiber backhaul<br/>to bound PoP (Frankfurt)
    Note over POP: HAS: BGP routing table

    UT->>IS: Uplink packet (best elevation satellite)
    Note right of UT: Physical selection:<br/>highest elevation angle

    IS->>ISL: Forward to nearest GS<br/>(shortest ISL path)
    ISL->>ES: Hop-by-hop to egress<br/>(~5-15ms ISL delay)

    ES->>GS: Downlink to Frankfurt GS<br/>(~2ms downlink)

    GS->>POP: Fiber backhaul to PoP Frankfurt<br/>(~1ms backhaul)
    Note over GS,POP: GS-PoP binding is FIXED<br/>(physical fiber)

    rect rgb(255, 230, 230)
        Note over POP,G: UNOPTIMIZED GROUND PATH<br/>Frankfurt -> Mountain View = ~105ms RTT
        POP->>G: Terrestrial internet routing<br/>(BGP, ~105ms ground RTT)
    end

    G-->>POP: Response
    POP-->>GS: Reverse path
    GS-->>ES: Uplink
    ES-->>ISL: ISL return
    ISL-->>IS: Hop-by-hop
    IS-->>UT: Downlink to terminal

    Note over UT,G: TOTAL E2E RTT ~ 121ms<br/>Satellite: ~16ms (short path) | Ground: ~105ms (LONG path)<br/>PoP = nearest to USER, NOT to destination
